After two years teaching, during which time Dalton was tutored by the Quaker naturalist Elihu Robinson, he worked as a farm laborer for a year, and then accepted a teaching job at the new Quaker-sponsored school in Kendal, where he remained for 12 years (1781-1793.) The school, whose benefactors included entrepreneurs such as Darby, was equipped by the Quakers and boasted an extensive library, which included the works Newton, and scientific equipment, which offered a stimulating atmosphere to the young Dalton.
